A 'Papilio demodocus' is a species of butterfly that belongs to the Papilionidae family.
This butterfly is mostly found in African countries such as Angola, Zambia, Tanzania, and South Africa.
The wingspan of a 'Papilio demodocus' can range from 8 to 11 cm.
The upper side of its wings has a black and white pattern with yellow-green spots, while the undersides have similar patterns but in grayish tones.
The wings of this butterfly have a sleek texture and a elongated triangular shape.
The 'Papilio demodocus' is known for its ability to mimic other butterflies' appearance, making it difficult for predators to detect it.
This butterfly is often found in lush green forests and savannahs, where it feeds on nectar and fruit juices.
